CONSTELLATION POWER SOURCE GENERATION, LLC FERC RATE SCHEDULE NO. 2

Reactive Supply and Voltage Control from Generation Sources Service

Constellation Power Source Generation, LLC ( CPSG ) provides Reactive Supply and Voltage Control from Generation Sources Service ( Reactive Supply Service ) from certain generation facilities ( Facilities ) within the Baltimore Gas and Electricity Company zone under the operational control of PJM Interconnection, L.L.C. This FERC Rate Schedule No. 2 sets forth CPSG s revenue requirement for Reactive Supply Service from the Facilities. This Rate Schedule shall be effective upon the date authorized by the Federal Energy Regulatory Commission.

CPSG s monthly fixed revenue requirement consists of the sum of the charges for the Facilities specified below.

PARTIAL MONTH REVENUE REQUIREMENT:
When a unit deactivation date is other than the first day of the month, the revenue requirement shall be a blended revenue requirement for the month of service in which the deactivation occurred ( Deactivation Month ) as follows: the sum of (i) the total monthly revenue requirement prior to the rate change divided by the number of days in the Deactivation Month, with the quotient then multiplied by the number of days in the Deactivation Month prior to the unit deactivation date and (ii) the total monthly revenue requirement after the rate change divided by the number of days in the Deactivation Month, with the quotient then multiplied by the remaining number of days in the Deactivation Month from and including the unit deactivation date.

FERC ELECTRIC TARIFF
1. Availability. Seller will make available under this Tariff for wholesale sales to any purchaser for resale (i) electric capacity, (ii) electric energy, and (iii) the following Ancillary Services:
(A) PJM: Seller offers regulation and frequency response service, energy imbalance service, and operating reserve service (which includes spinning, 10-minute, and 30-minute reserves) for sale into the market administered by PJM Interconnection, L.L.C. ("PJM") and, where the PJM Open Access Transmission Tariff permits, the self-supply of these services to purchasers for a bilateral sale that is used to satisfy the ancillary services requirements of the PJM Office of Interconnection. (B) New England: Seller offers regulation and frequency response service (automatic generator control), operating reserve service (which includes 10-minute spinning reserve, 10-minute non-spinning reserve, and 30-minute operating reserve service) to purchasers within the markets administered by the ISO New England, Inc. (C) New York: Seller offers regulation and frequency response service, and operating reserve service (which include 10-minute non-synchronous, 30-minute operating reserves, 10-minute spinning reserves, and 10-minute non-spinning reserves) for sale to purchasers in the market administered by the New York Independent System Operator, Inc.
(D) California: Seller offers regulation service, spinning reserve service, and non-spinning reserve service to the California Independent System Operator Corporation ("CAISO") and to others that are self-supplying ancillary services to the CAISO.
2. Applicability. This Tariff is applicable to all wholesale sales of each of the services listed in Paragraph 1 of this Tariff.
3. Rates. All sales shall be made at the rates established between Seller and the purchaser.
4. Terms and Conditions. All terms and conditions of sale shall be established between purchaser and Seller.
5. Compliance with Commission Regulations. Seller shall comply with the provisions of 18 CFR Part 35, Subpart H, as applicable, and with any conditions the Commission imposes in its orders concerning seller's market-based rate authority, including orders in which the Commission authorizes seller to engage in affiliate sales under this tariff or otherwise restricts or limits the seller's market-based rate authority. Failure to comply with the applicable provisions of 18 CFR Part 35, Subpart H, and with any orders of the Commission concerning seller's market-based rate authority, will constitute a violation of this tariff.
6. Limitations and Exemptions Regarding Market-Based Rate Authority. > Seller has requested and been granted (1) waiver of Subparts B and C of Part 35 of the Commission's regulations, except as to sections 35.12(a), 35.13(b), 35.15 and 35.16; (2) waiver of Parts 41, 101 and 141 of the Commission's accounting and reporting regulations, with the exception of 18 C.F.R. ?? 141.14, 141.15, and with the exception that waiver of the provisions of Part 101 that apply to hydropower licenses is not granted with respect to licensed hydropower projects; and (3) blanket authorization for all future issuances of securities or assumptions of liabilities pursuant to Part 34 of the Commission's regulations. See AmerGen VT, LLC, 90 FERC 61,307, on reh'g, Baltimore Gas & Elec. Co., 91 FERC 61,270 (2000). 7. Effective Date. This Tariff shall become effective on the date specified by FERC.
8. Seller Category. Seller is a Category 1 Seller in the Central, Northwest, Southeast, Southwest, and Southwest Power Pool regions, and a Category 2 Seller in the Northeast region, as defined in 18 C.F.R. ? 35.36(a).
